# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: data-deficient
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] In ecology, **local abundance** is the relative representation of a species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] It is usually measured as the number of individuals found per sample.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] The ratio of abundance of one species to one or multiple other species living in an ecosystem is referred to as relative species abundances.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] Both indicators are relevant for computing biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] A variety of sampling methods are used to measure abundance.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] For larger animals, these may include spotlight counts, track counts and roadkill counts, as well as presence at monitoring stations.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] In many plant communities the abundances of plant species are measured by plant cover, i.e. the relative area covered by different plant species in a small plot.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] Abundance is in simplest terms usually measured by identifying and counting every individual of every species in a given sector.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] It is common for the distribution of species to be skewed so that a few species take up the bulk of individuals collected.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] Relative species abundance is calculated by dividing the number of species from one group by the total number of species from all groups.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] These measures are all a part of community ecology.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] Understanding patterns within a community is easy when the community has a relatively low number of species.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] However most communities do not have a low number of species.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] Measuring species abundance allows for understanding of how species are distributed within an ecosystem.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] For example, salt water marshes have an influx of sea water, causing only a few species which are adapted to be able to survive in both salt and fresh water to be abundant.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] Inversely in land locked wetlands, the species abundance is more evenly distributed among the species who live within the wetland.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] In most ecosystems in which abundance has been calculated, most often only a small number of species are abundant, while a large number are pretty rare.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] These abundant species are often generalists, with many rare species being specialists.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] High density of a species in multiple localities will usually lead to it being relatively abundant over all in an ecosystem.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] Therefore, high local abundance can be directly linked to high regional distribution.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] Species with high abundance are likely to have more offspring, and these offspring in turn are more likely to colonize a new sector of the ecosystem than a species which is less abundant.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] Thus begins a positive feedback loop leading to a species distribution in which a few "core species" are wide spread, and the other species are restricted and scarce known as satellite species.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] Species abundance distribution (SAD) is one of the main uses of this measurement.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] SAD is a measurement of how common, or rare species are within an ecosystem.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] This allows researchers to assess how different species are distributed throughout an ecosystem.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] SAD is one of the most basic measurements in ecology and is used very often, therefore many different methods of measurement and analysis have developed.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] There are several methods for measuring abundance.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] An example of this is Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] These are measurement methods which involve estimation based on viewing a specific area of a designated size.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] The two Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings used are known as the D.A.F.O.R, and the A.C.F.O.R.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] These methods are useful for getting a rough estimate of the species abundance in a designated area (quadrant), but they are not exact or objective measurements.
[src:data-deficient/abundance-ecology] Therefore, if another method of measuring abundance is available, it should be used, as this will lead to more useful and quantifiable data.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] The project was an initiative of Wildscreen, a UK-registered educational charity, based in Bristol.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] The technical platform was created by Hewlett-Packard, as part of the HP Labs' Digital Media Systems research programme.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] It was a member of the Institutional Council of the Encyclopedia of Life.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] Two ARKive layers for Google Earth, featuring endangered species and species in the Gulf of Mexico were produced by Google Earth Outreach.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] The first of these was launched in April 2008 by Wildscreen's Patron, Sir David Attenborough.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] Due to lack of funding, the website was closed on 15 February 2019 and the media collection taken offline.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] Its successor, Wildscreen ARK (https://wildscreenark.org/), was launched in February 2024.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] The project formally was launched on 20 May 2003 by its patron, the UK-based natural history presenter, Sir David Attenborough, a long-standing colleague and friend of its chief instigator, the late Christopher Parsons, a former Head of the BBC Natural History Unit.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] Parsons never lived to see the fruition of the project, succumbing to cancer in November 2002 at the age of 70.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] Parsons identified a need to provide a centralised safe haven for wildlife films and photographs after discovering that many such records are held in scattered, non-indexed, collections, often with little or no public access, and sometimes in conditions that could lead to loss or damage.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] He believed the records could be a powerful force in building environmental awareness by bringing scientific names to life.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] He also saw their preservation as an important educational resource and conservation tool, not at least because extinction rates and habitat destruction could mean that images and sounds might be the only legacy of some species' existence.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] Media was digitised to the highest available quality without compression and encoded to open standards.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] A prototype site was online as early as April 1999.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] There were several design iterations before the formal launch.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] By the launch date, the project team had researched, catalogued, copied, described and authenticated image, sound and fact files of 1,000 animals, plants and fungi, many of them critically endangered.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] More multi-media profiles are added every month, starting with British flora and fauna and with species included on the Red List – that is, species that are believed to be closest to extinction, according to research by the World Conservation Union.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] By January 2006, the database had grown to 2,000 species, 15,000 still images and more than 50 hours of videos.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] By 2010, over 5,500 donors had contributed 70,000 film clips and photos of more than 12,000 species.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] In February 2019, Wildscreen announced that they "...have had to make the very hard decision to close the Arkive website on 15 February 2019", due to funding issues.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] The site was *Sunday Times* website of the year for 2005.
[src:data-deficient/arkive] It was a 2010 Webby Award honouree for its outstanding calibre of work, in the 'Education' category, and a 2010 Association of Educational Publishers 'Distinguished Achievement Award' winner, in the category for websites for 9-to-12-year-olds.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] A **biodiversity action plan** (**BAP**) is an internationally recognized program aimed at protecting and restoring threatened species and habitats, and at strengthening the resilience of biological systems.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The concept emerged from the 1992 Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD), which called on participating nations to develop strategies for conserving biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] As of 2009, 191 countries had ratified the CBD, although only a portion of them had produced comprehensive BAP documents.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] A fundamental method of engagement to a BAP is thorough documentation regarding individual species, with emphasis upon the population distribution and conservation status.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] This task, while fundamental, is highly daunting, since only an estimated ten percent of the world's species are believed to have been characterized as of 2006, most of these unknowns being fungi, invertebrate animals, micro-organisms and plants.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] For many bird, mammal and reptile species, information is often available in published literature; however, for fungi, invertebrate animals, micro-organisms and many plants, such information may require considerable local data collection.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] It is also useful to compile time trends of population estimates in order to understand the dynamics of population variability and vulnerability.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] In some parts of the world complete species inventories are not realistic; for example, in the Madagascar dry deciduous forests, many species are completely undocumented and much of the region has never even been systematically explored by scientists.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] A species plan component of a country's BAP should ideally entail a thorough description of the range, habitat, behaviour, breeding and interaction with other species.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Once a determination has been made of conservation status (e.g. rare, endangered, threatened, vulnerable), a plan can then be created to conserve and restore the species population to target levels.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The plan should also articulate which public and private agencies should implement the protection strategy and indicate budgets available to execute this strategy.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Agricultural practices can reduce the biodiversity of a region significantly.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Biodiversity Action Plans for agricultural production are necessary to ensure a biodiversity friendly production.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] It has not been common for companies to integrate biodiversity aspects into their value chain, but some companies and organizations have shown overall efforts for implementing better practices.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] An existing example for guidelines on biodiversity practices in agriculture is the Biodiversity Action Plan for spice production in India.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] By planning and implementing biodiversity friendly measures, farmers can mitigate negative impacts and support positive influences.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Where a number of threatened species depend upon a specific habitat, it may be appropriate to prepare a habitat protection element of the Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Examples of such special habitats are: raised acidic bogs of Scotland; Waterberg Biosphere bushveld in South Africa; California's coastal wetlands; and Sweden's Stora Alvaret on the island of Öland.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] In this case also, careful inventories of species and also the geographic extent and quality of the habitat must be documented.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Then, as with species plans, a program can be created to protect, enhance and/or restore habitat using similar strategies as discussed above under the species plans.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Some examples of individual countries which have produced substantive Biodiversity Action Plans follow.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] In every example the plans concentrate on plants and vertebrate animals, with very little attention to neglected groups such as fungi, invertebrate animals and micro-organisms, even though these are also part of biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Preparation of a country BAP may cost up to 100 million pounds sterling, with annual maintenance costs roughly ten percent of the initial cost.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] If plans took into account neglected groups, the cost would be higher.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Obviously costs for countries with small geographical area or simplified ecosystems have a much lesser cost.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP has been costed in the area of several million pounds sterling.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Australia has developed a detailed and rigorous Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] This document estimates that the total number of indigenous species may be 560,000, many of which are endemic.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] A key element of the BAP is protection of the Great Barrier Reef, which is actually in a much higher state of health than most of the world's reefs, Australia having one of the highest percentages of treated wastewater.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] There are however serious ongoing concerns, particularly in regards to the ongoing negative impact on water quality from land use practices.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Also, climate change impact is feared to be significant.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Considerable analysis has been conducted on the sustainable yield of firewood production, a major threat to deforestation in most tropical countries.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Biological inventory work; assessment of harvesting practices; and computer modeling of the dynamics of treefall, rot and harvest; have been carried out to adduce data on safe harvesting rates.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Extensive research has also been conducted on the relation of brush clearance to biodiversity decline and impact on water tables; for example, these effects have been analyzed in the Toolibin Lake wetlands region.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] New Zealand has ratified the Convention on Biological Diversity and as part of The New Zealand Biodiversity Strategy and Biodiversity Action Plans are implemented on ten separate themes.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Local government and some companies also have their own Biodiversity Action Plan.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP recognizes impacts of large numbers of tourists to the marine and coastal diversity of the Soufrière area of the country.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The BAP specifically acknowledges that the carrying capacity for human use and water pollution discharge of sensitive reef areas was exceeded by the year 1990.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The plan also addresses conservation of the historic island fishing industry.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] In 1992, several institutions in conjunction with native fishermen to produce a sustainable management plan for fishery resources, embodied in the Soufrière Marine Management Area.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Lucia BAP features significant involvement from the University of the West Indies.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Specific detailed attention is given to three species of threatened marine turtles, to a variety of vulnerable birds and a number of pelagic fishes and cetaceans.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] In terms of habitat conservation the plan focusses attention on the biologically productive mangrove swamps and notes that virtually all mangrove areas had already come under national protection by 1984.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The Tanzania national BAP addresses issues related to sustainable use of Lake Manyara, an extensive freshwater lake, whose usage by humans accelerated in the period 1950 to 1990.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The designation of the Lake Manyara Biosphere Reserve under UNESCO's Man and the Biosphere Programme in 1981 combines conservation of the lake and surrounding high value forests with sustainable use of the wetlands area and simple agriculture.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] This BAP has united principal lake users in establishing management targets.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The biosphere reserve has induced sustainable management of the wetlands, including monitoring groundwater and the chemistry of the escarpment water source.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The United Kingdom Biodiversity Action Plan covers not only terrestrial species associated with lands within the UK, but also marine species and migratory birds, which spend a limited time in the UK or its offshore waters.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The UK plan encompasses "391 Species Action Plans, 45 Habitat Action Plans and 162 Local Biodiversity Action Plans with targeted actions".
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] This plan is noteworthy because of its extensive detail, clarity of endangerment mechanisms, specificity of actions, follow up monitoring program and its inclusion of migrating cetaceans and pelagic birds.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] On August 28, 2007, the new Biodiversity Action Plan (BAP) [launched in 1997] identified 1,149 species and 65 habitats in the UK that needed conservation and greater protection.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The updated list included the hedgehog, house sparrow, grass snake and the garden tiger moth, while otters, bottlenose dolphins and red squirrels remained in need of habitat protection.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] In May 2011, the European Commission adopted a new strategy to halt the loss of biodiversity and ecosystem services in the EU by 2020, in line with the commitments made at the 10th meeting of the Convention on Biological Diversity (CBD) held in Nagoya, Japan in 2010.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] In 2012 the UK BAP was succeeded by the 'UK Post-2010 Biodiversity Framework'.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] To support the work of the UK BAP, the UK BAP website was created by JNCC in 2001.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The website contained information on the BAP process, hosted all relevant documents, and provided news and relevant updates.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] In March 2011, as part of the UK government's review of websites, the UK BAP site was ‘closed’, and the core content was migrated into the JNCC website.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Content from the original UK BAP website has been archived by the National Archives as snapshots from various dates (for example, UK *BAP*: copy March 2011; copy 2012).
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Twenty-six years prior to the international biodiversity convention, the United States had launched a national program to protect threatened species in the form of the 1966 Endangered Species Act.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The legislation created broad authority for analyzing and listing species of concern, and mandated that Species Recovery Plans be created.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Thus, while the USA is an unratified signer of the accord, arguably it has the longest track record and most comprehensive program of species protection of any country.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] There are about 7000 listed species (e.g. endangered or threatened), of which about half have approved Recovery Plans.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] While this number of species seems high compared to other countries, the value is rather indicative of the total number of species characterized, which is extremely large.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Five major divisions of habitat have been identified in Uzbekistan’s BAP: Wetlands (including reed habitat and man-made marsh); desert ecosystems (including sandy, stony and clay); steppes; riparian ecosystems; and mountain ecosystems.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Over 27,000 species have been inventoried in the country, with a high rate of endemism for fishes and reptiles.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Principal threats to biodiversity are related to human activities associated with overpopulation and generally related to agricultural intensification.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Major geographic regions encompassed by the BAP include the Aral Sea Programme (threatened by long-term drainage and salination, largely for cotton production), the Nuratau Biosphere Reserve, and the Western Tien Shan Mountains Programme (in conjunction with Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan).
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Some developing countries criticize the emphasis of BAPs, because these plans inherently favour consideration of wildlife protection above food and industrial production, and in some cases may represent an obstacle to population growth.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The plans are costly to produce, a fact which makes it difficult for many smaller countries and poorer countries to comply.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] In terms of the plans themselves, many countries have adopted pro-forma plans including little research and even less in the way of natural resource management.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Almost universally, this has resulted in plans which emphasize plants and vertebrate animals, and which overlook fungi, invertebrate animals and micro-organisms.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] With regard to specific world regions, there is a notable lack of substantive participation by most of the Middle Eastern countries and much of Africa, the latter of which may be impeded by economic considerations of plan preparation.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Some governments such as the European Union have diverted the purpose of a biodiversity action plan, and implemented the convention accord by a set of economic development policies with referencing certain ecosystems' protection.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The definition of biodiversity under the Convention on Biological Diversity now recognises that biodiversity is a combination of ecosystem structure and function, as much as its components e.g. species, habitats and genetic resources.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Biodiversity and wildlife are not the same thing.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The traditional focus on threatened species in BAPs is at odds with the principles of biodiversity management because, by the time species become threatened, the processes that maintain biodiversity are already compromised.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Individual species are also regarded as generally poor indicators of biodiversity when it comes to actual planning.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] A species approach to BAPs only serves to identify and at best, apply a patch to existing problems.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Increasingly, biodiversity planners are looking through the lens of ecosystem services.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Critics of biodiversity are often confusing the need to protect species (their intrinsic value) with the need to maintain ecosystem processes, which ultimately maintain human society and do not compromise economic development.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Hence, a core principle of biodiversity management, that traditional BAPs overlook, is the need to incorporate cultural, social and economic values in the process.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Modern day BAPs use an analysis of ecosystem services, key ecological process drivers, and use species as one of many indicators of change.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] They would seek to maintain structure and function by addressing habitat connectivity and resilience and may look at communities of species (threatened or otherwise) as one method of monitoring outcomes.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Ultimately, species are the litmus test for biodiversity – viable populations of species can only be expected to exist in relatively intact habitats.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] However, the rationale behind BAPs is to "conserve and restore" biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] One of the fastest developing areas of management is biodiversity offsets.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] The principles are in keeping with ecological impact assessment, which in turn depends on good quality BAPs for evaluation.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-action-plan] Contemporary principles of biodiversity management, such as those produced by the Business Biodiversity Offsets Program are now integral to any plans to manage biodiversity, including the development of BAPs.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Since life began on Earth, six major mass extinctions and several minor events have led to large and sudden drops in biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The Phanerozoic aeon (the last 540 million years) marked a rapid growth in biodiversity via the Cambrian explosion.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] In this period, the majority of multicellular phyla first appeared.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The next 400 million years included repeated, massive biodiversity losses.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Those events have been classified as mass extinction events.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] In the Carboniferous, rainforest collapse may have led to a great loss of plant and animal life.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The Permian–Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago, was the worst; vertebrate recovery took 30 million years.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have led to an ongoing biodiversity loss and an accompanying loss of genetic diversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This process is often referred to as Holocene extinction, or the *sixth mass extinction*.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] For example, it was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Destroying habitats for farming is a key reason why biodiversity is decreasing today.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This can be seen for example in the effects of climate change on biomes.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This anthropogenic extinction may have started toward the end of the Pleistocene, as some studies suggest that the megafaunal extinction event that took place around the end of the last ice age partly resulted from overhunting.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biologists most often define *biodiversity* as the "totality of genes, species and ecosystems of a region".
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] (2011), there are approximately 8.7 million terrestrial species and 2.2 million oceanic species.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The authors note that these estimates are strongest for eukaryotic organisms and likely represent the lower bound of prokaryotic diversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Since the rate of extinction has increased, many extant species may become extinct before they are described.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Not surprisingly, in the Animalia the most studied groups are birds and mammals, whereas fishes and arthropods are the least studied animal groups.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] During the last century, decreases in biodiversity have been increasingly observed.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] It was estimated in 2007 that up to 30% of all species will be extinct by 2050.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Of these, about one eighth of known plant species are threatened with extinction.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Estimates reach as high as 140,000 species per year (based on Species-area theory).
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This figure indicates unsustainable ecological practices, because few species emerge each year.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The rate of species loss is greater now than at any time in human history, with extinctions occurring at rates hundreds of times higher than background extinction rates. and expected to still grow in the upcoming years.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] As of 2012, some studies suggest that 25% of all mammal species could be extinct in 20 years.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] According to a 2016 study by the World Wildlife Fund, population abundance among 3,706 monitored vertebrate species is exhibiting a persistent downward trend.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The *Living Planet Report 2014* claims that "the number of mammals, birds, reptiles, amphibians, and fish across the globe is, on average, about half the size it was 40 years ago".
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Of that number, 39% accounts for the terrestrial wildlife gone, 39% for the marine wildlife gone and 76% for the freshwater wildlife gone.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity took the biggest hit in Latin America, plummeting 83 percent.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] High-income countries showed a 10% increase in biodiversity, which was canceled out by a loss in low-income countries.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This is despite the fact that high-income countries use five times the ecological resources of low-income countries, which was explained as a result of a process whereby wealthy nations are outsourcing resource depletion to poorer nations, which are suffering the greatest ecosystem losses.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] A 2017 study published in *PLOS One* found that the biomass of insect life in Germany had declined by three-quarters in the last 25 years.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Dave Goulson of Sussex University stated that their study suggested that humans "appear to be making vast tracts of land inhospitable to most forms of life, and are currently on course for ecological Armageddon.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] In 2020 the World Wildlife Fund published a report saying that "biodiversity is being destroyed at a rate unprecedented in human history".
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The report claims that 68% of the population of the examined species were destroyed in the years 1970 – 2016.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Of 70,000 monitored species, around 48% are experiencing population declines from human activity (in 2023), whereas only 3% have increasing populations.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Rates of decline in biodiversity in the current sixth mass extinction match or exceed rates of loss in the five previous mass extinction events in the fossil record.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity loss is in fact "one of the most critical manifestations of the Anthropocene" (since around the 1950s); the continued decline of biodiversity constitutes "an unprecedented threat" to the continued existence of human civilization.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The reduction is caused primarily by human impacts, particularly habitat destruction.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Since the Stone Age, species loss has accelerated above the average basal rate, driven by human activity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of species losses are at a rate 100–10,000 times as fast as is typical in the fossil record.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Loss of biodiversity results in the loss of natural capital that supplies ecosystem goods and services.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Species today are being wiped out at a rate 100 to 1,000 times higher than baseline, and the rate of extinctions is increasing.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This process destroys the resilience and adaptability of life on Earth.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] In 2006, many species were formally classified as rare or endangered or threatened; moreover, scientists have estimated that millions more species are at risk which have not been formally recognized.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] About 40 percent of the 40,177 species assessed using the IUCN Red List criteria are now listed as threatened with extinction—a total of 16,119.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] As of late 2022 9251 species were considered part of the IUCN's critically endangered.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Numerous scientists and the IPBES *Global Assessment Report on Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services* assert that human population growth and overconsumption are the primary factors in this decline.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] However, other scientists have criticized this finding and say that loss of habitat caused by "the growth of commodities for export" is the main driver.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] A 2025 study found that human activities are responsible for biodiversity loss across all species and ecosystems.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is an important driver of global biodiversity loss because of its impacts on ecosystems.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] At the same time, biodiversity and climate are closely interconnected, as biodiversity influences the mitigation and adaptation potential of ecosystems.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] For more information on these interactions, see the 'Regulating services' section below.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Other studies, however, have pointed out that habitat destruction for the expansion of agriculture and the overexploitation of wildlife are the more significant drivers of contemporary biodiversity loss, not climate change.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is not evenly distributed, rather it varies greatly across the globe as well as within regions and seasons.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Among other factors, the diversity of all living things (biota) depends on temperature, precipitation, altitude, soils, geography and the interactions between other species.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The study of the spatial distribution of organisms, species and ecosystems, is the science of biogeography.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Diversity consistently measures higher in the tropics and in other localized regions such as the Cape Floristic Region and lower in polar regions generally.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Rain forests that have had wet climates for a long time, such as Yasuní National Park in Ecuador, have particularly high biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] There is local biodiversity, which directly impacts daily life, affecting the availability of fresh water, food choices, and fuel sources for humans.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Regional biodiversity includes habitats and ecosystems that synergizes and either overlaps or differs on a regional scale.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] National biodiversity within a country determines the ability for a country to thrive according to its habitats and ecosystems on a national scale.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Also, within a country, endangered species are initially supported on a national level then internationally.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Ecotourism may be utilized to support the economy and encourages tourists to continue to visit and support species and ecosystems they visit, while they enjoy the available amenities provided.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] International biodiversity impacts global livelihood, food systems, and health.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Problematic pollution, over consumption, and climate change can devastate international biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Nature-based solutions are a critical tool for a global resolution.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Many species are in danger of becoming extinct and need world leaders to be proactive with the Kunming-Montreal Global Biodiversity Framework.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Terrestrial biodiversity is thought to be up to 25 times greater than ocean biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Forests harbour most of Earth's terrestrial biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The conservation of the world's biodiversity is thus utterly dependent on the way in which we interact with and use the world's forests.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] A new method used in 2011, put the total number of species on Earth at 8.7 million, of which 2.1 million were estimated to live in the ocean.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] However, this estimate seems to under-represent the diversity of microorganisms.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Forests provide habitats for 80 percent of amphibian species, 75 percent of bird species and 68 percent of mammal species.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] About 60 percent of all vascular plants are found in tropical forests.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Mangroves provide breeding grounds and nurseries for numerous species of fish and shellfish and help trap sediments that might otherwise adversely affect seagrass beds and coral reefs, which are habitats for many more marine species.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Forests span around 4 billion acres (nearly a third of the Earth's land mass) and are home to approximately 80% of the world's biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] About 1 billion hectares are covered by primary forests.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Over 700 million hectares of the world's woods are officially protected.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of forests varies considerably according to factors such as forest type, geography, climate and soils – in addition to human use.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Areas with dense human populations and intense agricultural land use, such as Europe, parts of Bangladesh, China, India and North America, are less intact in terms of their biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Northern Africa, southern Australia, coastal Brazil, Madagascar and South Africa, are also identified as areas with striking losses in biodiversity intactness.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] European forests in EU and non-EU nations comprise more than 30% of Europe's land mass (around 227 million hectares), representing an almost 10% growth since 1990.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Generally, there is an increase in biodiversity from the poles to the tropics.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Thus localities at lower latitudes have more species than localities at higher latitudes.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This is often referred to as the latitudinal gradient in species diversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Several ecological factors may contribute to the gradient, but the ultimate factor behind many of them is the greater mean temperature at the equator compared to that at the poles.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Even though terrestrial biodiversity declines from the equator to the poles, some studies claim that this characteristic is unverified in aquatic ecosystems, especially in marine ecosystems.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The latitudinal distribution of parasites does not appear to follow this rule.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Also, in terrestrial ecosystems the soil bacterial diversity has been shown to be highest in temperate climatic zones, and has been attributed to carbon inputs and habitat connectivity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] In 2016, an alternative hypothesis ("the fractal biodiversity") was proposed to explain the biodiversity latitudinal gradient.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] In this study, the species pool size and the fractal nature of ecosystems were combined to clarify some general patterns of this gradient.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This hypothesis considers temperature, moisture, and net primary production (NPP) as the main variables of an ecosystem niche and as the axis of the ecological hypervolume.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] In this way, it is possible to build fractal hyper volumes, whose fractal dimension rises to three moving towards the equator.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] A biodiversity hotspot is a region with a high level of endemic species that have experienced great habitat loss.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The term hotspot was introduced in 1988 by Norman Myers.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] While hotspots are spread all over the world, the majority are forest areas and most are located in the tropics.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Brazil's Atlantic Forest is considered one such hotspot, containing roughly 20,000 plant species, 1,350 vertebrates and millions of insects, about half of which occur nowhere else.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The island of Madagascar and India are also particularly notable.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Colombia is characterized by high biodiversity, with the highest rate of species by area unit worldwide and it has the largest number of endemics (species that are not found naturally anywhere else) of any country.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] About 10% of the species of the Earth can be found in Colombia, including over 1,900 species of bird, more than in Europe and North America combined, Colombia has 10% of the world's mammals species, 14% of the amphibian species and 18% of the bird species of the world.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Madagascar dry deciduous forests and lowland rainforests possess a high ratio of endemism.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Since the island separated from mainland Africa 66 million years ago, many species and ecosystems have evolved independently.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Indonesia's 17,000 islands cover 735,355 square miles (1,904,560 km2) and contain 10% of the world's flowering plants, 12% of mammals and 17% of reptiles, amphibians and birds—along with nearly 240 million people.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Many regions of high biodiversity and/or endemism arise from specialized habitats which require unusual adaptations, for example, alpine environments in high mountains, or Northern European peat bogs.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Accurately measuring differences in biodiversity can be difficult.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Selection bias amongst researchers may contribute to biased empirical research for modern estimates of biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is the result of 3.5 billion years of evolution.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The origin of life has not been established by science, however, some evidence suggests that life may already have been well-established only a few hundred million years after the formation of the Earth.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Until approximately 2.5 billion years ago, all life consisted of microorganisms – archaea, bacteria, and single-celled protozoans and protists.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity grew fast during the Phanerozoic (the last 540 million years), especially during the so-called Cambrian explosion—a period during which nearly every phylum of multicellular organisms first appeared.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] However, recent studies suggest that this diversification had started earlier, at least in the Ediacaran, and that it continued in the Ordovician.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Over the next 400 million years or so, invertebrate diversity showed little overall trend and vertebrate diversity shows an overall exponential trend.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This dramatic rise in diversity was marked by periodic, massive losses of diversity classified as mass extinction events.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The worst was the Permian-Triassic extinction event, 251 million years ago.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Vertebrates took 30 million years to recover from this event.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The most recent major mass extinction event, the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, occurred 66 million years ago.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This period has attracted more attention than others because it resulted in the extinction of the non-avian dinosaurs, which were represented by many lineages at the end of the Maastrichtian, just before that extinction event.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] However, many other taxa were affected by this crisis, which affected even marine taxa, such as ammonites, which also became extinct around that time.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The biodiversity of the past is called Paleobiodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The fossil record suggests that the last few million years featured the greatest biodiversity in history.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] However, not all scientists support this view, since there is uncertainty as to how strongly the fossil record is biased by the greater availability and preservation of recent geologic sections.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Some scientists believe that corrected for sampling artifacts, modern biodiversity may not be much different from biodiversity 300 million years ago, whereas others consider the fossil record reasonably reflective of the diversification of life.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Estimates of the present global macroscopic species diversity vary from 2 million to 100 million, with a best estimate of somewhere near 9 million, the vast majority arthropods.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Diversity appears to increase continually in the absence of natural selection.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The existence of a *global carrying capacity*, limiting the amount of life that can live at once, is debated, as is the question of whether such a limit would also cap the number of species.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] While records of life in the sea show a logistic pattern of growth, life on land (insects, plants and tetrapods) shows an exponential rise in diversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] It also appears that the diversity continues to increase over time, especially after mass extinctions.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] On the other hand, changes through the Phanerozoic correlate much better with the hyperbolic model (widely used in population biology, demography and macrosociology, as well as fossil biodiversity) than with exponential and logistic models.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The latter models imply that changes in diversity are guided by a first-order positive feedback (more ancestors, more descendants) and/or a negative feedback arising from resource limitation.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Hyperbolic model implies a second-order positive feedback.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Differences in the strength of the second-order feedback due to different intensities of interspecific competition might explain the faster rediversification of ammonoids in comparison to bivalves after the end-Permian extinction.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic pattern of the world population growth arises from a second-order positive feedback between the population size and the rate of technological growth.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The hyperbolic character of biodiversity growth can be similarly accounted for by a feedback between diversity and community structure complexity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The similarity between the curves of biodiversity and human population probably comes from the fact that both are derived from the interference of the hyperbolic trend with cyclical and stochastic dynamics.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Most biologists agree however that the period since human emergence is part of a new mass extinction, named the Holocene extinction event, caused primarily by the impact humans are having on the environment.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] It has been argued that the present rate of extinction is sufficient to eliminate most species on the planet Earth within 100 years.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] New species are regularly discovered (on average between 5–10,000 new species each year, most of them insects) and many, though discovered, are not yet classified (estimates are that nearly 90% of all arthropods are not yet classified).
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Most of the terrestrial diversity is found in tropical forests and in general, the land has more species than the ocean; some 8.7 million species may exist on Earth, of which some 2.1 million live in the ocean.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] It is estimated that 5 to 50 billion species have existed on the planet.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Assuming that there may be a maximum of about 50 million species currently alive, it stands to reason that greater than 99% of the planet's species went extinct prior to the evolution of humans.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Estimates on the number of Earth's current species range from 10 million to 14 million, of which about 1.2 million have been documented and over 86% have not yet been described.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] However, a May 2016 scientific report estimates that 1 trillion species are currently on Earth, with only one-thousandth of one percent described.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The total amount of related DNA base pairs on Earth is estimated at 5.0 × 1037 and weighs 50 billion tonnes.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] In comparison, the total mass of the biosphere has been estimated to be as much as four trillion tons of carbon.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] In July 2016, scientists reported identifying a set of 355 genes from the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all organisms living on Earth.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The age of Earth is about 4.54 billion years.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The earliest undisputed evidence of life dates at least from 3.7 billion years ago, during the Eoarchean era after a geological crust started to solidify following the earlier molten Hadean eon.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] There are microbial mat fossils found in 3.48 billion-year-old sandstone discovered in Western Australia.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Other early physical evidence of a biogenic substance is graphite in 3.7 billion-year-old meta-sedimentary rocks discovered in Western Greenland.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] More recently, in 2015, "remains of biotic life" were found in 4.1 billion-year-old rocks in Western Australia.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] There have been many claims about biodiversity's effect on the ecosystem services, especially *provisioning* and *regulating services*.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Some of those claims have been validated, some are incorrect and some lack enough evidence to draw definitive conclusions.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Experiments with controlled environments have shown that humans cannot easily build ecosystems to support human needs; for example insect pollination cannot be mimicked, though there have been attempts to create artificial pollinators using unmanned aerial vehicles.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The economic activity of pollination alone represented between $2.1–14.6 billion in 2003.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Other sources have reported somewhat conflicting results and in 1997 Robert Costanza and his colleagues reported the estimated global value of ecosystem services (not captured in traditional markets) at an average of $33 trillion annually.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity plays a role in multiple ecological regulating services that strengthen the stability, functioning and adaptability of ecosystems.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] For example, plant species richness can increase functional diversity in many ecosystems.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Different plant organisms living together can perform complementary roles such as nutrient cycling and water regulation, which can contribute to the stabilisation of ecosystem processes under climate stress, a mechanism known as niche complementarity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This could include enhanced transpiration and soil moisture regulation, as more efficient water use can be promoted by the variety of different leaf traits and root depths, which in turn can reduce drought stress and mitigate heat impact.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Climate change is also associated with higher pathogen pressure on terrestrial and marine ecosystems.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] In many ecosystems higher biodiversity could contribute to greater resilience to pests and diseases, as diversity in host traits and interactions can interrupt disease spread and reduce the severity of the outbreak.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] In coastal ecosystems genetic diversity within a species can further enhance its adaptive capacity by providing a range of traits that support populations to persist under changing temperature and precipitation regimes.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Furthermore, in terrestrial ecosystems higher biodiversity can promote mutualistic interactions (like pollination or mycorrhizal networks), which can enhance nutrient uptake and support overall productivity and resilience.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The other category of agricultural diversity is called interspecific diversity and refers to the number and types of different species.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Agricultural diversity can also be divided by whether it is 'planned' diversity or 'associated' diversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This is a functional classification that we impose and not an intrinsic feature of life or diversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Associated biodiversity can be damaging or beneficial.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The beneficial associated biodiversity include for instance wild pollinators such as wild bees and syrphid flies that pollinate crops and natural enemies and antagonists to pests and pathogens.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Beneficial associated biodiversity occurs abundantly in crop fields and provide multiple ecosystem services such as pest control, nutrient cycling and pollination that support crop production.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Although about 80 percent of humans' food supply comes from just 20 kinds of plants, humans use at least 40,000 species.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Earth's surviving biodiversity provides resources for increasing the range of food and other products suitable for human use, although the present extinction rate shrinks that potential.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's relevance to human health is becoming an international political issue, as scientific evidence builds on the global health implications of biodiversity loss.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Some of the health issues influenced by biodiversity include dietary health and nutrition security, infectious disease, medical science and medicinal resources, social and psychological health.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is also known to have an important role in reducing disaster risk, including rising sea levels.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] For example, wetland ecosystems along coastal communities serve as excellent water filtration systems, storage, and ultimately create a buffer region between the ocean and mainland neighborhoods in order to prevent water reaching these communities under climate change pressures or storm surges.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Other examples of diverse species or organisms are present around the world, offering their resourceful utilities to provide protection of human survival.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity provides critical support for drug discovery and the availability of medicinal resources.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Only a tiny fraction of wild species has been investigated for medical potential.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This process of bioprospecting can increase biodiversity loss, as well as violating the laws of the communities and states from which the resources are taken.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] According to the Boston Consulting Group, in 2021, the economic value that biodiversity has on society comes down to four definable terms: regulation, culture, habitat, and provisioning.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] To sum these up in a relatively short manner, biodiversity helps maintain habitat and animal functions that provide considerable amounts of resources that benefit the economy.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity's economic resources are worth at around $150 trillion annually which is roughly twice the world's GDP.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The loss of biodiversity is actually harming the GDP of the world by costing an estimated $5 trillion annually.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Business supply chains rely heavily on ecosystems remaining relatively maintained and nurtured.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] A disruption to these supply chains would negatively impact many businesses that would end up costing them more than what they are gaining.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Philosophically it could be argued that biodiversity has intrinsic aesthetic and spiritual value to mankind *in and of itself*.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This idea can be used as a counterweight to the notion that tropical forests and other ecological realms are only worthy of conservation because of the services they provide.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity also affords many non-material benefits including spiritual and aesthetic values, knowledge systems and education.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] A variety of objective means exist to empirically measure biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Each measure relates to a particular use of the data, and is likely to be associated with the variety of genes.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity is commonly measured in terms of taxonomic richness of a geographic area over a time interval.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] In order to calculate biodiversity, species evenness, species richness, and species diversity are to be obtained first.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] *Species evenness* is the relative number of individuals of each species in a given area.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] *Species richness* is the number of species present in a given area.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] *Species diversity* is the relationship between species evenness and species richness.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] There are many ways to measure biodiversity within a given ecosystem.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] However, the two most popular are Shannon-Weaver diversity index, commonly referred to as Shannon diversity index, and the other is Simpsons diversity index.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Although many scientists prefer to use Shannon's diversity index simply because it takes into account species richness.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Less than 1% of all species that have been described have been studied beyond noting their existence.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The vast majority of Earth's species are microbial.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Contemporary biodiversity physics is "firmly fixated on the visible [macroscopic] world".
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] For example, microbial life is metabolically and environmentally more diverse than multicellular life (see e.g., extremophile).
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] "On the tree of life, based on analyses of small-subunit ribosomal RNA, visible life consists of barely noticeable twigs.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The inverse relationship of size and population recurs higher on the evolutionary ladder—to a first approximation, all multicellular species on Earth are insects".
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Insect extinction rates are high—supporting the Holocene extinction hypothesis.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Biodiversity naturally varies due to seasonal shifts.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Spring's arrival enhances biodiversity as numerous species breed and feed, while winter's onset temporarily reduces it as some insects perish and migrating animals leave.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Additionally, the seasonal fluctuation in plant and invertebrate populations influences biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Barriers such as large rivers, seas, oceans, mountains and deserts encourage diversity by enabling independent evolution on either side of the barrier, via the process of allopatric speciation.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The term invasive species is applied to species that breach the natural barriers that would normally keep them constrained.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Without barriers, such species occupy new territory, often supplanting native species by occupying their niches, or by using resources that would normally sustain native species.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Species are increasingly being moved by humans (on purpose and accidentally).
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Some studies say that diverse ecosystems are more resilient and resist invasive plants and animals.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Many studies cite effects of invasive species on natives, but not extinctions.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Invasive species seem to increase local (alpha diversity) diversity, which decreases turnover of diversity (beta diversity).
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Overall gamma diversity may be lowered because species are going extinct because of other causes, but even some of the most insidious invaders (e.g.: Dutch elm disease, emerald ash borer, chestnut blight in North America) have not caused their host species to become extinct.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Extirpation, population decline and homogenization of regional biodiversity are much more common.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Human activities have frequently been the cause of invasive species circumventing their barriers, by introducing them for food and other purposes.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Human activities therefore allow species to migrate to new areas (and thus become invasive) occurred on time scales much shorter than historically have been required for a species to extend its range.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] At present, several countries have already imported so many exotic species, particularly agricultural and ornamental plants, that their indigenous fauna/flora may be outnumbered.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] For example, the introduction of kudzu from Southeast Asia to Canada and the United States has threatened biodiversity in certain areas.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Another example are pines, which have invaded forests, shrublands and grasslands in the southern hemisphere.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Endemic species can be threatened with extinction through the process of genetic pollution, i.e. uncontrolled hybridization, introgression and genetic swamping.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Genetic pollution leads to homogenization or replacement of local genomes as a result of either a numerical and/or fitness advantage of an introduced species.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Hybridization and introgression are side-effects of introduction and invasion.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] These phenomena can be especially detrimental to rare species that come into contact with more abundant ones.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The abundant species can interbreed with the rare species, swamping its gene pool.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] This problem is not always apparent from morphological (outward appearance) observations alone.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Some degree of gene flow is normal adaptation and not all gene and genotype constellations can be preserved.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] However, hybridization with or without introgression may, nevertheless, threaten a rare species' existence.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology matured in the mid-20th century as ecologists, naturalists and other scientists began to research and address issues pertaining to global biodiversity declines.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] The conservation ethic advocates management of natural resources for the purpose of sustaining biodiversity in species, ecosystems, the evolutionary process and human culture and society.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Conservation biology is reforming around strategic plans to protect biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Preserving global biodiversity is a priority in strategic conservation plans that are designed to engage public policy and concerns affecting local, regional and global scales of communities, ecosystems and cultures.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Action plans identify ways of sustaining human well-being, employing natural capital, macroeconomic policies including economic incentives, and ecosystem services.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] In the EU Directive 1999/22/EC zoos are described as having a role in the preservation of the biodiversity of wildlife animals by conducting research or participation in breeding programs.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Removal of exotic species will allow the species that they have negatively impacted to recover their ecological niches.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Exotic species that have become pests can be identified taxonomically (e.g., with Digital Automated Identification SYstem (DAISY), using the barcode of life).
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] Removal is practical only given large groups of individuals due to the economic cost.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p01] As sustainable populations of the remaining native species in an area become assured, "missing" species that are candidates for reintroduction can be identified using databases such as the *Encyclopedia of Life* and the Global Biodiversity Information Facility.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas, including forest reserves and biosphere reserves, serve many functions including for affording protection to wild animals and their habitat.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas have been set up all over the world with the specific aim of protecting and conserving plants and animals.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Some scientists have called on the global community to designate as protected areas of 30 percent of the planet by 2030, and 50 percent by 2050, in order to mitigate biodiversity loss from anthropogenic causes.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] The target of protecting 30% of the area of the planet by the year 2030 (30 by 30) was adopted by almost 200 countries in the 2022 United Nations Biodiversity Conference.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] At the moment of adoption (December 2022) 17% of land territory and 10% of ocean territory were protected.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] In a study published 4 September 2020 in Science Advances researchers mapped out regions that can help meet critical conservation and climate goals.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Protected areas safeguard nature and cultural resources and contribute to livelihoods, particularly at local level.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] There are over 238 563 designated protected areas worldwide, equivalent to 14.9 percent of the earth's land surface, varying in their extension, level of protection, and type of management (IUCN, 2018).
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of protected areas extend beyond their immediate environment and time.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] In addition to conserving nature, protected areas are crucial for securing the long-term delivery of ecosystem services.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] They provide numerous benefits including the conservation of genetic resources for food and agriculture, the provision of medicine and health benefits, the provision of water, recreation and tourism, and for acting as a buffer against disaster.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Increasingly, there is acknowledgement of the wider socioeconomic values of these natural ecosystems and of the ecosystem services they can provide.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] A national park is a large natural or near natural area set aside to protect large-scale ecological processes, which also provide a foundation for environmentally and culturally compatible, spiritual, scientific, educational, recreational and visitor opportunities.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] These areas are selected by governments or private organizations to protect natural biodiversity along with its underlying ecological structure and supporting environmental processes, and to promote education and recreation.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] The International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN), and its World Commission on Protected Areas (WCPA), has defined "National Park" as its Category II type of protected areas.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Wildlife sanctuaries are areas of either shelter for animals who are unable to live in the wild on their own, or they are temporary rehabilitation centers for wildlife to improve in their overall health and wellbeing.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Both of these serve as places in which biodiversity can be preserved rather than harmed.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] According to an article published in the National Park Service website, national parks aim their resources at maintaining animal and habitat integrity through conservation and preservation of their ecosystems.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] This along with educating the general public on wildlife functions, the aim for an increase in biodiversity is one of many goals trying to be focused on through national parks.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Forest protected areas are a subset of all protected areas in which a significant portion of the area is forest.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] This may be the whole or only a part of the protected area.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Globally, 18 percent of the world's forest area, or more than 700 million hectares, fall within legally established protected areas such as national parks, conservation areas and game reserves.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] There is an estimated 726 million ha of forest in protected areas worldwide.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Of the six major world regions, South America has the highest share of forests in protected areas, 31 percent.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] The forests play a vital role in harboring more than 45,000 floral and 81,000 faunal species of which 5150 floral and 1837 faunal species are endemic.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] In addition, there are 60,065 different tree species in the world.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Plant and animal species confined to a specific geographical area are called endemic species.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] In forest reserves, rights to activities like hunting and grazing are sometimes given to communities living on the fringes of the forest, who sustain their livelihood partially or wholly from forest resources or products.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Approximately 50 million hectares (or 24%) of European forest land is protected for biodiversity and landscape protection.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Forests allocated for soil, water, and other ecosystem services encompass around 72 million hectares (32% of European forest area).
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] It stated that "the state of nature has deteriorated at an unprecedented and accelerating rate".
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] To fix the problem, humanity will need a transformative change, including sustainable agriculture, reductions in consumption and waste, fishing quotas and collaborative water management.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive is playing a role in mainstreaming the goals of the Global Biodiversity Framework (GBF) for biodiversity.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] The aim of mainstreaming is to embed biodiversity considerations into public and private practice to conserve and sustainably use biodiversity on global and local levels.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] The concept of nature-positive refers to the societal goal to halt and reverse biodiversity loss, measured from a baseline of 2020 levels, and to achieve full so-called "nature recovery" by 2050.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Citizen science, also known as public participation in scientific research, has been widely used in environmental sciences and is particularly popular in a biodiversity-related context.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] It has been used to enable scientists to involve the general public in biodiversity research, thereby enabling the scientists to collect data that they would otherwise not have been able to obtain.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Volunteer observers have made significant contributions to on-the-ground knowledge about biodiversity, and recent improvements in technology have helped increase the flow and quality of occurrences from citizen sources.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] A 2016 study published in Biological Conservation registers the massive contributions that citizen scientists already make to data mediated by the Global Biodiversity Information Facility (GBIF).
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Despite some limitations of the dataset-level analysis, it is clear that nearly half of all occurrence records shared through the GBIF network come from datasets with significant volunteer contributions.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Recording and sharing observations are enabled by several global-scale platforms, including iNaturalist and eBird.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Global agreements such as the Convention on Biological Diversity, give "sovereign national rights over biological resources" (not property).
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] The agreements commit countries to "conserve biodiversity", "develop resources for sustainability" and "share the benefits" resulting from their use.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Biodiverse countries that allow bioprospecting or collection of natural products, expect a share of the benefits rather than allowing the individual or institution that discovers/exploits the resource to capture them privately.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Bioprospecting can become a type of biopiracy when such principles are not respected.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Sovereignty principles can rely upon what is better known as Access and Benefit Sharing Agreements (ABAs).
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] The Convention on Biodiversity implies informed consent between the source country and the collector, to establish which resource will be used and for what and to settle on a fair agreement on benefit sharing.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] The agreement includes also recovering 30% of earth degraded ecosystems and increasing funding for biodiversity issues.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] In May 2020, the European Union published its Biodiversity Strategy for 2030.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] The biodiversity strategy is an essential part of the climate change mitigation strategy of the European Union.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] From the 25% of the European budget that will go to fight climate change, large part will go to restore biodiversity and nature based solutions.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Approximately half of the global GDP depend on nature.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] In Europe many parts of the economy that generate trillions of euros per year depend on nature.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] The benefits of Natura 2000 alone in Europe are €200 – €300 billion per year.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Uniform approval for use of biodiversity as a legal standard has not been achieved, however.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] Bosselman argues that biodiversity should not be used as a legal standard, claiming that the remaining areas of scientific uncertainty cause unacceptable administrative waste and increase litigation without promoting preservation goals.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] India passed the Biological Diversity Act in 2002 for the conservation of biological diversity in India.
[src:data-deficient/biodiversity-p02] The Act also provides mechanisms for equitable sharing of benefits from the use of traditional biological resources and knowledge.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] See Late Quaternary prehistoric birds for birds which disappeared in prehistoric and early historic times, usually due to human activity (i.e., starting with the Upper Paleolithic Revolution).
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] For birds having gone extinct in modern times (since 1500), see List of extinct birds.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Since the Late Pleistocene period, it is estimated that 1,430 (95% credible interval: 1327–1544) bird extinctions have occurred.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Human activity has been directly attributed to almost all bird species extinctions, specifically prehistoric and early historical species.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] During the Upper Paleolithic period, human societies began spreading across the globe, leading to the overhunting of species and the introduction of invasive species to new environments.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] A particularly significant period of extinction occurred when humans colonized the islands of Melanesia, Polynesia, and Micronesia around 4,000 years ago.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] According to a study published in *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*, early Polynesian settlers are often credited with contributing to the extinction of over 1,000 bird species during this time, majority of which were non-passerine land birds.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Before the Industrial Revolution (1750-1850), most bird species were not yet heavily impacted by habitat loss or climate change.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] However, overexploitation through hunting, bird collecting, as well as the introduction of invasive species became significant threats.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Industrialization marked a turning point in the relationship between humans and birds.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The technological growth, urban expansion, and increased emissions from industrial activity caused widespread habitat destruction and altered ecosystems.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] In the United Kingdom, species such as the white-tailed eagle (*Haliaeetus albicilla*) and cranes, for example, were recognized as more abundant before industrialization began.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] By the 19th century, the advent of industrial-scale hunting and urban sprawl had put pressure on many bird populations.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The species' final extinction came in the early 20th century, though causes remain unclear.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Similarly, the passenger pigeon (*Ectopistes migratorius*) once one of the most populous bird species in North America, was driven to extinction in the early 20th century due to relentless hunting and habitat loss.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] This extinction served as a stark reminder of the fragility of bird populations in the face of human intervention.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The loss of such a previously abundant species helped catalyze the first major bird conservation efforts in the United States.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Following the assumed extinction of passenger pigeons, Theodore Roosevelt claimed to have witnessed a small flock of the birds at his family name’s rural cabin in Virginia some 25 years after their extinction (March 24, 1900).
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Following this sighting, Theodore recognized the severity of the loss of this once abundant species and initiated strengthened bird advocacy legislation during his presidency in 1907.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The establishment of the first Federal Bird Reserve on Pelican Island in Florida can be attributed to this sighting made by President Roosevelt.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The early 20th century saw the rise of formal conservation efforts.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The National Audubon Society, founded in 1905, played a key role in raising awareness about the rapid decline of bird populations, specifically in response to the exploitation of birds for the feather trade.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The organization's efforts were influential in propelling early legal protections for birds.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] A significant achievement in favor of bird protection was the passage of the Migratory Bird Treaty Act of 1918.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] This act provided international protection for migratory bird species between the United States, Canada, Mexico, Japan, and Russia.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] From the 1920s to 1950s, bird advocacy gained further strength.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] It sought to fund the protection of wetlands using hunter fees.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Additionally, during the Great Depression, New Deal programs including the Civilian Conservation Corps preserved wildlife refuges, providing birds a thriving environment for bird species.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Birdwatching gained popularity within this timeframe, too, in large part thanks to Roger Tory Peterson’s groundbreaking field guides.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Finally, Rachel Carson's early works began to clarify the relationship between healthy bird populations and a healthy planet.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] All of these factors laid more solid groundwork for the continuation of advocacy for birds.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The 1960s were a particularly pivotal era in favor of bird conservation.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The publication of Rachel Carson’s *Silent Spring* (1962) aided in exposing widespread dangers of pesticide use, particularly DDT, on bird populations.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Her groundbreaking work demonstrated how DDT led to the thinning of eggshells in species like the bald eagle (*Haliaeetus leucocephalus*) and peregrine falcon (*Falco peregrinus*), resulting in reproductive failures.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Carson’s book ignited a broader environmental movement, leading to significant policy changes, and the eventual DDT ban.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The Environmental Protection Agency enforced a generalized ban on DDT pesticides in 1972.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Bald eagles made a famous comeback during the “dirty sixties” thanks to this ban, along with the brown pelican (*Pelecanus occidentalis*) and peregrine falcon.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] By the 1980s, the global conservation movement gained further momentum.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Organizations like BirdLife International played an increasingly vital role in establishing international frameworks for bird protection.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] This included efforts to protect critical habitats, such as wetland areas, and to monitor at-risk species.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Additionally, the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) developed the Red List of Threatened Species, which continues to serve as an important tool for identifying and tracking species at risk of extinction, including many bird species.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The most critical threat facing threatened birds is the destruction and fragmentation of habitat.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The loss of forests, plains and other natural systems into agriculture, mines, and urban developments, the draining of swamps and other wetlands, and logging reduce potential habitat for many species.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] In addition the remaining patches of habitat are often too small or fragmented by the construction of roads or other such barriers that cause populations in these fragmented *islands* to become vulnerable to localized extinction.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] In addition many forest species show limited abilities to disperse and occupy new forest fragments (see island biogeography).
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The loss of tropical rainforest is the most pressing problem, as these forests hold the highest number of species yet are being destroyed quickly.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Habitat loss has been implicated in a number of extinctions, including the ivory-billed woodpecker (*Campephilus principalis*) (disputed because of "rediscovery"), Bachman's warbler (*Vermivora bachmanii*), and the dusky seaside sparrow (*Ammospiza maritima nigrescens*).
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Climate change is a catalyst for the worrying downward trend of bird populations globally.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The speed of human-caused climate change is currently unprecedented, leading bird species into continuously unadaptable circumstances.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] It has been observed that most North American bird species have been recognized over the prior few decades to have shifted their breeding ranges irregularly due to climate change.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Migratory birds are more prone to the effects of climate change, leading to shifts in time migratory patterns.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] It is predicted in the coming years that mountainous birds will even lose suitable migratory habitats due to rising temperatures at higher elevations.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] On top of these migratory shifts, global warming has been predicted to be changing size and wing length proportionally in all bird species.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] It is presumed that with rising temperatures, smaller birds maintain better competitive fitness thanks to their easier heat dispersal compared to their larger counterparts within the same species.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Indirect impacts of climate change on birds include increased drought and fires, rising-sea levels, increased disease, phenological mismatch, and uncommon interactions between species.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Increase in drought leads to increased fires, destroying nesting ground and fragmenting specifically sagebrush ecosystems.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Rise in sea-levels provides similar altercations for marsh-nesting birds.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Nesting sites disappear as sea-levels rise, eliminating habitats for nesting parents and young to continue species.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Phenological mismatch occurs due to rising temperatures shifting migratory timeframes but not quickly enough, altering the life cycle events in interacting species at different rates.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Birds are afflicted by numerous pollutants including marine oil pollution, plastic pollution, light pollution, sound pollution, air pollution, and pesticides to name a major few.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Plastic pollution serves a major detriment to birds, mainly marine birds.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Many marine birds suffer from entanglement, nutritional deprivation, and gut damage due to ingested plastic litter.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Historically the threat posed by introduced species has probably caused the most extinctions of birds, particularly on islands. most prehistoric human caused extinctions were insular as well.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Many island species evolved in the absence of predators and consequently lost many anti-predator behaviors.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] As humans traveled around the world they brought with them many foreign animals which disturbed these island species.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Some of these were unfamiliar predators, like rats, feral cats, and pigs; others were competitors, such as other bird species, or herbivores that degraded breeding habitat.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Disease can also play a role; introduced avian malaria is thought to be a primary cause of many extinctions in Hawaii.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Many species currently threatened with extinction are vulnerable to introduced species, such as the kōkako (*Callaeas* species), black robin *(Petroica traversi)*, Mariana crow (*Corvus kubaryi*), and the Hawaiian duck (*Anas wyvilliana*).
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Humans have exploited birds for a very long time, and sometimes this exploitation has resulted in extinction.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Overhunting occurred in some instances with a naive species unfamiliar with humans, such as the moa of New Zealand, in other cases it was an industrial level of hunting that led to extinction.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The passenger pigeon was once the most numerous species of bird alive (possibly ever), overhunting reduced a species that once numbered in the billions to extinction.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Hunting pressure can be for food, sport, feathers, or even come from scientists collecting museum specimens.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Collection of great auks for museums pushed the already rare species to extinction.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The harvesting of parrots for the pet trade has led to many species becoming endangered.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Between 1986 and 1988, two million parrots were legally imported into the US alone.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Parrots are also illegally smuggled between countries, and rarer species can command high prices.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Organized entrapment of birds takes place today across the globe, specifically in Latin America, Asia, and Africa.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The demand for exotic pet birds in the United States drives capture in Bolivia and Mexico, with a supposed over 22,000 individuals of 31 parrot species illegally traded under Bolivian law every year and an estimated 65,000–78,500 parrots captured every year in Mexico.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] This poaching continues due to the potential profits, with rarer species selling for up to $1,000 each when caught illegally.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Plume hunting is the hunting of wild birds to harvest their decorative feathers.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] More decorative plumes, which were sold for use as ornamentation particularly in hat-making, were more sought after in the trade.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] While the plume trade is not necessarily a large ongoing threat to birds, it was in its height in the late 19th century into the early 20th century until protective efforts were instated.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Hybridization may also endanger birds, damaging the gene stock.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] For example, the American black duck (*Anas rubripes*) has been often reported hybridizing with the mallard (*Anas platyrhynchos*), starting a slow decline in the rarer *A. rubripes*.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Gamebird hybrids are particularly common and many breeders produce hybrids that may be accidentally or intentionally introduced into the wild.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Pollution has led to serious declines in some species.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Increasingly large volumes of plastic waste are being transported by wind and ocean currents throughout the planet, and mistaken ingestion by many species is eventually fatal.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Seabirds are also vulnerable to oil spills, which destroy the plumage's waterproofing, causing the birds to drown or die of hypothermia.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Light pollution can also have a damaging effect on some species, particularly nocturnal seabirds such as petrels.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The pesticide DDT was responsible for thinning egg shells in nesting birds, particularly seabirds and birds of prey that are high on the food chain.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The use of pesticides continues to harm birds, especially insectivores like swallows that have lost a food source from the use of insecticides in agriculture.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] A particularly dangerous class of pesticides is the seed-coating neonicotinoids.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Neonicotinoids include a neurotoxin that bioaccumulates in the tissue of birds and is associated with impairment of reproduction.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Seabirds face another threat in the form of bycatch, where birds in the water become tangled in fishing nets or hooked on lines set out by long-line fisheries.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] As many as 100,000 albatrosses are hooked and drown each year on tuna lines set out by long-line fisheries.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Birds are also threatened by high rise buildings, communications towers, and other human-related activities and structures; estimates vary from about 3.5 to 975 million birds a year in the North America alone.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The largest source of human-related bird death is due to glass windows, which kill 100–900 million birds a year.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The next largest sources of human-caused death are hunting (100+ million), house cats (100 million), cars and trucks (50 to 100 million), electric power lines (174 million), and pesticides (67 million).
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Birds are also killed in large quantities by flying into communication tower guidelines, usually after being attracted by tower lights.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] This phenomenon is called towerkill and is responsible for 5–50 million birds deaths a year.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Similarly, natural gas flaring can attract and kill large numbers of birds.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Approximately 7,500 migrating songbirds were attracted to and killed by the flare at the liquefied natural gas terminal in Saint John, New Brunswick, Canada, on September 13, 2013.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Similar incidents have occurred at flares on offshore oil and gas installations.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The recent growth in the renewable energy industry is also increasing the threat to birds farther away from dense human population centers.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] As of late 2019, the capacity of wind power in the U.S. reached 100 GW (gigawatt).
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Studies conducted at a variety of farms found fewer than 14, and typically fewer than 4, direct bird deaths per year per installed megawatt; suggesting cumulative mortality is approaching the order of a million individuals annually.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Migrating songbirds appeared to be the most strongly impacted in some studies.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The primary impact of commercial solar farms – the majority utilizing photovoltaic collectors which are mounted near the ground – is from extensive land clearing and increases in long-distance power transmission infrastructure.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] According to a 2018 *Nature* paper studying trends in global waterbird populations, ineffective governance is a major driver of biodiversity loss in wetlands, highlighting the importance of political and institutional factors in conservation outcomes.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Scientists and conservation professionals have developed a number of techniques to protect bird species.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] These techniques have had varying levels of success.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Captive breeding, or *ex-situ* conservation, has been used in a number of instances to save species from extinction.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The principle is to create a viable population of a species in either zoos or breeding facilities, for later reintroduction back into the wild.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] A captive population can either serve as an insurance against the species going extinct in the wild or as a last-ditch effort in situations where conservation in the wild is impossible.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Captive breeding has been used to save several species from extinction, the most famous example being the California condor, a species that declined to less than thirty birds.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] In order to save the California condor the decision was made to take every individual left in the wild into captivity.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] From these 22 individuals a breeding program began that brought the numbers up to 273 by 2005.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] An even more impressive recovery was that of the Mauritius kestrel (*Falco punctatus*), which by 1974 had dropped to only four individuals, yet by 2006 the population increased to 800.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Reintroductions of captive bred populations can occur to replenish wild populations of an endangered species, to create new populations or to restore a species after it has become extinct in the wild.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Reintroductions helped bring the wild populations of Hawaiian geese (nene) (*Branta sandvicensis)* from 30 birds to over 500.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The Mauritius kestrel was successfully reintroduced into the wild after its captive breeding programme.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Reintroductions can be very difficult and often fail if insufficient preparations are made, as species born in captivity may lack the skills and knowledge needed for life in the wild after living in captivity.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Reintroductions can also fail if the causes of a birds decline have not been adequately addressed.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Attempts to reintroduce the Bali starling (*Leucopsar rothschildi*) into the wild failed due to continued poaching of reintroduced birds.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The introduction of captives of unknown pedigree can also pose a threat to native populations.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Domestic fowl have threatened endemic species such as *Gallus g. bankiva* while pheasants such as the ring-necked pheasant (*Phasianus colchicus*) and captive cheer pheasants (*Catreus wallichii*) of uncertain origin have escaped into the wild or have been intentionally introduced.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Green peafowl (*Pavo muticus*) of similar mixed origins confiscated from local bird dealers have been released into areas with native wild birds.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Translocations involve moving populations of threatened species into areas of suitable habitat currently unused by the species.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] There are several reasons for doing this; the creation of secondary populations that act as an insurance against disaster, or in many cases threats faced by the original population in its current location.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] One famous translocation was of the kākāpō (*Strigops habroptilus*) of New Zealand.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] These large flightless parrots were unable to cope with introduced predators in their remaining habitat on Stewart Island, so were moved to smaller offshore islands that had been cleared of predators.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] From there a recovery program has managed to maintain and eventually increase their numbers.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] As the loss and destruction of habitat is the most serious threat facing many bird species, conservation organizations and government agencies tasked with protecting birds work to protect areas of natural habitat.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] This can be achieved through purchasing land of conservation importance, setting aside land or gazetting it as a national park or other protected area, and passing legislation preventing landowners from undertaking damaging land use practices, or paying them not to undertake those activities.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] The goals of habitat protection for birds and other threatened animals and plants often conflicts with other stakeholders, such as landowners and businesses, who can face economically damaging restrictions on their activities.
[src:data-deficient/bird-conservation] Plans to protect crucial habitat for the spotted owl (*Strix occidentalis*) of North America required the protection of large areas of old growth forest in the western United States; this was opposed by logging companies who claimed it would cause job losses and reduced profits.
[src:data-deficient/blue-listed] The concept of a Blue List was derived in 1971 by Robert Arbib from the National Audubon Society in his article, "Announcing-- The Blue List: an 'early warning' system for birds".
[src:data-deficient/blue-listed] The article stated that the list was made up for species that appear to be locally common in North America, but is undergoing non-cyclic declines.
[src:data-deficient/blue-listed] Starting from 1971, it was utilized to list vulnerable bird species throughout North America.
[src:data-deficient/blue-listed] Unlike the US Fish and Wildlife Endangered Species List, the Blue List was made to identify **patterns** of population losses for regional bird populations before they could be listed as endangered.
[src:data-deficient/blue-listed] Every decade after its release, the list is revisited and revised based on regional editors and species get "nominated" to be added to the list.
[src:data-deficient/blue-listed] Using this metric reginal editors were able to report on the species along with their status ranks in order to identify the patterns of population growth that each species is facing.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Its aim is to ensure that international trade (import/export) in specimens of animals and plants included under CITES does not threaten the survival of the species in the wild.
[src:data-deficient/cites] This is achieved via a system of permits and certificates.
[src:data-deficient/cites] CITES affords varying degrees of protection to more than 40,900 species.
[src:data-deficient/cites] As of December 2024, the Secretary-General of CITES is Ivonne Higuero.
[src:data-deficient/cites] CITES is one of the largest and oldest conservation and sustainable use agreements in existence.
[src:data-deficient/cites] There are three working languages of the convention (English, French and Spanish) in which all documents are made available.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Participation is voluntary and countries that have agreed to be bound by the convention are known as Parties.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Although CITES is legally binding on the Parties, it does not take the place of national laws.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Rather it provides a framework respected by each Party, which must adopt their own domestic legislation to implement CITES at the national level.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Originally, CITES addressed depletion resulting from demand for luxury goods such as furs in Western countries, but with the rising wealth of Asia, particularly in China, the focus changed to products demanded there, particularly those used for luxury goods such as elephant ivory or rhinoceros horn.
[src:data-deficient/cites] As of 2022, CITES has expanded to include thousands of species previously considered unremarkable and in no danger of extinction such as manta rays.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The text of the convention was finalized at a meeting of representatives of 80 countries in Washington, D.C., United States, on 3 March 1973.
[src:data-deficient/cites] It was then open for signature until 31 December 1974.
[src:data-deficient/cites] It entered into force after the 10th ratification by a signatory country, on 1 July 1975.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Countries that signed the Convention become Parties by ratifying, accepting or approving it.
[src:data-deficient/cites] By the end of 2003, all signatory countries had become Parties.
[src:data-deficient/cites] States that were not signatories may become Parties by acceding to the convention.
[src:data-deficient/cites] As of June 2025, the convention has 185 parties, including 184 states and the European Union.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The CITES Convention includes provisions and rules for trade with non-Parties.
[src:data-deficient/cites] All member states of the United Nations are party to the treaty, with the exception of North Korea, Federated States of Micronesia, Haiti, Kiribati, Marshall Islands, Nauru, South Sudan, East Timor, and Tuvalu.
[src:data-deficient/cites] UN observer the Holy See is also not a member.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The Faroe Islands, an autonomous region in the Kingdom of Denmark, is also treated as a non-Party to CITES (both the Danish mainland and Greenland are part of CITES).
[src:data-deficient/cites] An amendment to the text of the convention, known as the Gaborone Amendment allows regional economic integration organizations (REIO), such as the European Union, to have the status of a member state and to be a Party to the convention.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The REIO can vote at CITES meetings with the number of votes representing the number of members in the REIO, but it does not have an additional vote.
[src:data-deficient/cites] In accordance with Article XVII, paragraph 3, of the CITES Convention, the Gaborone Amendment entered into force on 29 November 2013, 60 days after 54 (two-thirds) of the 80 States that were party to CITES on 30 April 1983 deposited their instrument of acceptance of the amendment.
[src:data-deficient/cites] At that time it entered into force only for those States that had accepted the amendment.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The amended text of the convention will apply automatically to any State that becomes a Party after 29 November 2013.
[src:data-deficient/cites] For States that became party to the convention before that date and have not accepted the amendment, it will enter into force 60 days after they accept it.
[src:data-deficient/cites] He was born in Bavaria, Germany and was educated in international law in Germany, France and Canada.
[src:data-deficient/cites] He became a professor and an author, focusing on environmental law, holding other positions such as the Director-General of the IUCN and legal advisor for environmental affairs to the World Bank.
[src:data-deficient/cites] A Canadian native, Lapointe served in the military for many years and acted as a diplomat before governing the CITES.
[src:data-deficient/cites] He is currently an author and holds the position of President of the IWMC World Conservation Trust, a non-profit organization that promotes wildlife conservation with an emphasis on a human-centered approach to natural-resources.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Born and raised in Bulgaria, Topkov was a diplomat before managing CITES, and was removed from that position following the misuse of permits that violated CITES guidelines.
[src:data-deficient/cites] A native of the Netherlands and graduate from the University of Amsterdam, Wijnsteker held the position of Secretary-General for the longest period of time and is now an author.
[src:data-deficient/cites] An Australian who studied environmental law, Scanlon was active in combating illegal animal trade and currently works in the effort to protect Elephants in Africa as CEO of the Elephant Protection Initiative Foundation (EPIF).
[src:data-deficient/cites] The first woman to hold this position, Higuero was educated in environmental economics and is from Panama.
[src:data-deficient/cites] CITES works by subjecting international trade in specimens of listed taxa to controls as they move across international borders.
[src:data-deficient/cites] CITES specimens can include a wide range of items including the whole animal/plant (whether alive or dead), or a product that contains a part or derivative of the listed taxa such as cosmetics or traditional medicines.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The CITES definition of "trade" does not require a financial transaction to be occurring.
[src:data-deficient/cites] All trade in specimens of species covered by CITES must be authorized through a system of permits and certificates prior to the trade taking place.
[src:data-deficient/cites] CITES permits and certificates are issued by one or more Management Authorities in charge of administering the CITES system in each country.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Management Authorities are advised by one or more Scientific Authorities on the effects of trade of the specimen on the status of CITES-listed species.
[src:data-deficient/cites] CITES permits and certificates must be presented to relevant border authorities in each country in order to authorize the trade.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Each party must enact their own domestic legislation to bring the provisions of CITES into effect in their territories.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Parties may choose to take stricter domestic measures than CITES provides (for example by requiring permits/certificates in cases where they would not normally be needed or by prohibiting trade in some specimens).
[src:data-deficient/cites] Over 40,900 species, subspecies and populations are protected under CITES.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Each protected taxa or population is included in one of three lists called Appendices.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The Appendix that lists a taxon or population reflects the level of the threat posed by international trade and the CITES controls that apply.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Taxa may be split-listed meaning that some populations of a species are on one Appendix, while some are on another.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*) is currently split-listed, with all populations except those of Botswana, Namibia, South Africa and Zimbabwe listed in Appendix I.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Those of Botswana, Namibia, South Africa and Zimbabwe are listed in Appendix II.
[src:data-deficient/cites] There are also species that have only some populations listed in an Appendix.
[src:data-deficient/cites] One example is the pronghorn (*Antilocapra americana*), a ruminant native to North America.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Its Mexican population is listed in Appendix I, but its U.S. and Canadian populations are not listed (though certain U.S. populations in Arizona are nonetheless protected under other domestic legislation, in this case the Endangered Species Act).
[src:data-deficient/cites] Taxa are proposed for inclusion, amendment or deletion in Appendices I and II at meetings of the Conference of the Parties (CoP), which are held approximately once every three years.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Amendments to listing in Appendix III may be made unilaterally by individual parties.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Appendix I taxa are those that are threatened with extinction and to which the highest level of CITES protection is afforded.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Commercial trade in wild-sourced specimens of these taxa is not permitted and non-commercial trade is strictly controlled by requiring an import permit and export permit to be granted by the relevant Management Authorities in each country before the trade occurs.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Appendix II taxa are those that are not necessarily threatened with extinction, but trade must be controlled in order to avoid utilization incompatible with their survival.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Appendix II taxa may also include species similar in appearance to species already listed in the Appendices.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The vast majority of taxa listed under CITES are listed in Appendix II.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Any trade in Appendix II taxa standardly requires a CITES export permit or re-export certificate to be granted by the Management Authority of the exporting country before the trade occurs.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Appendix III species are those that are protected in at least one country, and that country has asked other CITES Parties for assistance in controlling the trade.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Any trade in Appendix III species standardly requires a CITES export permit (if sourced from the country that listed the species) or a certificate of origin (from any other country) to be granted before the trade occurs.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Examples of species listed on Appendix III and the countries that listed them are the Hoffmann's two-toed sloth (*Choloepus hoffmanni*) by Costa Rica, sitatunga (*Tragelaphus spekii*) by Ghana and African civet (*Civettictis civetta*) by Botswana.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Under Article VII, the Convention allows for certain exceptions to the general trade requirements described above.
[src:data-deficient/cites] CITES provides for a special process for specimens that were acquired before the provisions of the Convention applied to that specimen.
[src:data-deficient/cites] These are known as "pre-Convention" specimens and must be granted a CITES pre-Convention certificate before the trade occurs.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Only specimens legally acquired before the date on which the species concerned was first included in the Appendices qualify for this exemption.
[src:data-deficient/cites] CITES provides that the standard permit/certificate requirements for trade in CITES specimens do not generally apply if a specimen is a personal or household effect.
[src:data-deficient/cites] However, there are a number of situations where permits/certificates for personal or household effects are required and some countries choose to take stricter domestic measures by requiring permits/certificates for some or all personal or household effects.
[src:data-deficient/cites] CITES allows trade in specimens to follow special procedures if Management Authorities are satisfied that they are sourced from captive bred animals or artificially propagated plants.
[src:data-deficient/cites] In the case of commercial trade of Appendix I taxa, captive bred or artificially propagated specimens may be traded as if they were Appendix II.
[src:data-deficient/cites] This reduces the permit requirements from two permits (import/export) to one (export only).
[src:data-deficient/cites] In the case of non-commercial trade, specimens may be traded with a certificate of captive breeding/artificial propagation issued by the Management Authority of the state of export in lieu of standard permits.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Standard CITES permit and certificates are not required for the non-commercial loan, donation or exchange between scientific or forensic institutions that have been registered by a Management Authority of their State.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Consignments containing the specimens must carry a label issued or approved by that Management Authority (in some cases Customs Declaration labels may be used).
[src:data-deficient/cites] Specimens that may be included under this provision include museum, herbarium, diagnostic and forensic research specimens.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Registered institutions are listed on the CITES website.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Amendments to the Convention must be supported by a two-thirds majority who are "present and voting" and can be made during an extraordinary meeting of the COP if one-third of the Parties are interested in such a meeting.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The Gaborone Amendment (1983) allows regional economic blocs to accede to the treaty.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Trade with non-Party states is allowed, although permits and certificates are recommended to be issued by exporters and sought by importers.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Species in the Appendices may be proposed for addition, change of Appendix, or de-listing (i.e., deletion) by any Party, whether or not it is a range State and changes may be made despite objections by range States if there is sufficient (2/3 majority) support for the listing.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Species listings are made at the Conference of Parties.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Upon acceding to the convention or within 90 days of a species listing being amended, Parties may make reservations.
[src:data-deficient/cites] In these cases, the party is treated as being a state that is not a Party to CITES with respect to trade in the species concerned.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Notable reservations include those by Iceland, Japan, and Norway on various baleen whale species and those on Falconiformes by Saudi Arabia.
[src:data-deficient/cites] As of 2002, 50% of Parties lacked one or more of the four major CITES requirements - designation of Management and Scientific Authorities; laws prohibiting the trade in violation of CITES; penalties for such trade and laws providing for the confiscation of specimens.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Although the Convention itself does not provide for arbitration or dispute in the case of noncompliance, 36 years of CITES in practice has resulted in several strategies to deal with infractions by Parties.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The Secretariat, when informed of an infraction by a Party, will notify all other parties.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The Secretariat will give the Party time to respond to the allegations and may provide technical assistance to prevent further infractions.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Other actions the Convention itself does not provide for but that derive from subsequent COP resolutions may be taken against the offending Party.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Bilateral sanctions have been imposed on the basis of national legislation (e.g. the USA used certification under the Pelly Amendment to get Japan to revoke its reservation to hawksbill turtle products in 1991, thus reducing the volume of its exports).
[src:data-deficient/cites] Infractions may include negligence with respect to permit issuing, excessive trade, lax enforcement, and failing to produce annual reports (the most common).
[src:data-deficient/cites] It does not explicitly address market demand.
[src:data-deficient/cites] In fact, CITES listings have been demonstrated to increase financial speculation in certain markets for high value species.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Funding does not provide for increased on-the-ground enforcement (it must apply for bilateral aid for most projects of this nature).
[src:data-deficient/cites] There has been increasing willingness within the Parties to allow for trade in products from well-managed populations.
[src:data-deficient/cites] For instance, sales of the South African white rhino have generated revenues that helped pay for protection.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Listing the species on Appendix I increased the price of rhino horn (which fueled more poaching), but the species survived wherever there was adequate on-the-ground protection.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Thus field protection may be the primary mechanism that saved the population, but it is likely that field protection would not have been increased without CITES protection.
[src:data-deficient/cites] In another instance, the United States initially stopped exports of bobcat and lynx hides in 1977 when it first implemented CITES for lack of data to support no detriment findings.[1] However, in this Federal Register notice, issued by William Yancey Brown, the U.S.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Management programs for these species expanded rapidly, including tagging for export, and are currently recognized in program approvals under regulations of the U.S.
[src:data-deficient/cites] By design, CITES regulates and monitors trade in the manner of a "negative list" such that trade in all species is permitted and unregulated *unless* the species in question appears on the Appendices or looks very much like one of those taxa.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Then and only then, trade is regulated or constrained.
[src:data-deficient/cites] For example, recently several bird classified as threatened with extinction appeared in the legal wild bird trade because the CITES process never considered their status.
[src:data-deficient/cites] If a "positive list" approach were taken, only species evaluated and approved for the positive list would be permitted in trade, thus lightening the review burden for member states and the Secretariat, and also preventing inadvertent legal trade threats to poorly known species.
[src:data-deficient/cites] In order to ensure that the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) was not violated, the Secretariat of GATT was consulted during the drafting process.
[src:data-deficient/cites] During the coronavirus pandemic in 2020 CEO Ivonne Higuero noted that illegal wildlife trade not only helps to destroy habitats, but these habitats create a safety barrier for humans that can prevent pathogens from animals passing themselves on to people.
[src:data-deficient/cites] CITES would benefit from access to Global Environment Facility (GEF), funds-although this is difficult given the GEFs more ecosystem approach-or other more regular funds.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Development of a future mechanism similar to that of the Montreal Protocol (developed nations contribute to a fund for developing nations) could allow more funds for non-Secretariat activities.
[src:data-deficient/cites] In the 1990s the annual trade of legal animal products was $160 billion annually.
[src:data-deficient/cites] In 2009 the estimated value almost doubled to $300 billion.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Additional information about the documented trade can be extracted through queries on the CITES website.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The Conference of the Parties (CoP) is held once every three years.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The location of the next CoP is chosen at the close of each CoP by a secret ballot vote.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The CITES Committees (Animals Committee, Plants Committee and Standing Committee) hold meetings during each year that does not have a CoP, while the Standing committee meets also in years with a CoP.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The Committee meetings take place in Geneva, Switzerland (where the Secretariat of the CITES Convention is located), unless another country offers to host the meeting.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The Secretariat is administered by UNEP.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The Animals and Plants Committees have sometimes held joint meetings.
[src:data-deficient/cites] The previous joint meeting was held in March 2012 in Dublin, Ireland, and the latest one was held in Veracruz, Mexico, in May 2014.
[src:data-deficient/cites] A current list of upcoming meetings appears on the CITES calendar.
[src:data-deficient/cites] At the seventeenth Conference of the Parties (CoP 17), Namibia and Zimbabwe introduced proposals to amend their listing of elephant populations in Appendix II.
[src:data-deficient/cites] Instead, they wished to establish controlled trade in all elephant specimens, including ivory.
[src:data-deficient/cites] They argue that revenue from regulated trade could be used for elephant conservation and rural communities' development.
[src:data-deficient/cites] However, both proposals were opposed by the US and other countries.
[src:data-deficient/data-deficient] A **data deficient** (**DD**) species is one which has been categorized by the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) as offering insufficient information for a proper assessment of conservation.
[src:data-deficient/data-deficient] DD species may have been extensively studied, but in some cases little or no information is available on the abundance and distribution of the species.
[src:data-deficient/data-deficient] It can also indicate uncertainty about the taxonomic classification of an organism; for example, the IUCN classifies the orca as "data deficient" because of the likelihood that two or more types of the whale are separate species.
